 image denied reflective access to closureClass.getDeclaredMethod, causing the test to fail. I'll need to explore Groovy's public API instead of relying on Java reflection, especially using InvokerHelper.invokeStaticMethod. Understanding the dynamic access coverage mechanism through static instrumentation of class$ Class.forName seems crucial.\"},{\"type\":\"summary_text\",\"text\":\"**Exploring reflection and coverage issues**\\n\\nIt seems like the test might ignore direct reflection if the class name doesn't match. This could be due to metadata not being generated, and the native execution might not be possible because it's inaccessible. Also, if the target source root already has many untracked tests, the new file may not have been tracked, even though it is under test source.\\n\\nThe second prompt suggests an external workflow ran after the first attempt, but it still didn't cover the test. Maybe the test failed to compile due to the `rootPath` method being unavailable in the chain. If it doesn't compile, the workflow might skip coverage entirely.  \\n\\nThere were attempts noted, but if Java reflection access to class$ isn’t registered, that could cause a NoSuchMethodException. It sounds like the public API part might have run, yet it didn't trigger class$. I need to find a way to trigger class$ without relying on direct Java or native reflection.\"},{\"type\":\"summary_text\",\"text\":\"**Considering class$ invocation**\\n\\nI'm wondering how class$ can be invoked without using reflection. Since it's a static package-private method, I can't call it from outside the package, and I can't place the test in the same package. Maybe I could use MethodHandles? It feels sort of reflection-esque, but still involves metadata, which might not be allowed.\\n\\nCould Groovy's dynamic method call `InvokerHelper.invokeStaticMethod` help? It seems like this might not need the same native reflect metadata, which could be a workaround I should explore!\"}]}"}, {"type": "toolC